<p> ECGViewer imports different formats of ECG data (ranging from 8 to 120 leads) collected from experiments and performs initial processing and annotation. This prepares the data for further use in computation. Its main function includes:
<ol>
<li>Noise removal: including several different methods such as Butterworth, wavelet, and FFT based filtering. </li>

<li>Baseline correction: including several options such as polynomial detrend, harmonic detrend, median offset, and constant offset. </li>

<li>Annotation and interpolation of bad leads. </li>

<li>Manual annotation of QRST segment in the ECG. </li>

<li>Importing a variety of lead layouts and formats, as well as a user-written, customizable plug-in to support the reading of new data format. </li>

<li>Exporting bad leads, annotations, and lead data in a simple format. </li>

</ol>

<br> Check out the source code on <a href= "https://github.com/RaineForest/ECG-Viewer">Github</a>!
</p>
<!-- End of ECG Viewer -->
</div>

<!-- Start of CUDA -->
<h2 class="title">2. <a name="cuda">CUDA Acceleration for Compute-Intensive Applications</a> </h2>
<br>
<div>

<p>By utilizing the massively parallel operation of the GPU, compute-intensive applications such as TEPI can be executed much faster than a standard sequential approach.  Using nVidia's CUDA technology, matrix operations can take a fraction of the time compared to a conventional CPU. In a previous CUDA conversion of TEPI (relevant publication), the use of GPU accelerates the computation of TEPI from ~200 hours (on 2 x 3 GHz Quad-Core Intel Xeon) to ~ 20-120 minutes (on a NVIDIA Tesla K20m card). </p>
<p>
Example publications & software:

<a href = "images/Accelerating noninvasive transmural electrophysiological imaging.pdf" > <br>Martin Corraine, Sonia Lopez, and Linwei Wang: GPU Accelerations of Transmural Electrophysiological Imaging. Computing in Cardiology (CinC), 2012, Pp 849-952</a></p>


</div>

